<br>
Paranoia-<br>
<br>
“He’s been in there for days, and he refuses to come out for anything other than food, drink, or dragging in the occasional corpse…” a voice murmured, the acoustics of the hallway carrying his voice throughout the entire stretch. <br>
<br>
The temple of Ro was quiet today, unlike many other days when explosions would rock the inner sanctums of the carved-out structure of rock.<br>
<br>
“Maybe it’s best to let him play. A child without his tinker toys is not a very happy one. Besides, I really don’t want to piss off Trilkin again today. True, he’s not the most powerful of enchanters, but he does seem to hold a grudge…” the voice’s cohort echoed in response.<br>
<br>
Light from the torches shined on the dual, elven faces, their pale complexion tinted with the deep, coarse reds of the lava pools around them. Pointed, well shaped ears crown their heads, covered in a shaggy fur of white, and tied back loosely with a piece of cloth, letting their hair messily fall across their crimson robes. The crimson stain of Ro’s insignia seems to be all over this place, the scent of fire easily overcoming anyone new to these places. Of course, the indigenous imps and populance of the temple are so heavily used to it. One would think they’d have died of lung cancer by now…<br>
<br>
BANG!<br>
<br>
Well, so much for the peace…<br>
<br>
“Not again… Now what’d he do…” one of the elves muttered to himself, both of them rushing towards the back of the temple, sprinting quickly through the halls in a heated run.<br>
<br>
The staggering, and slightly burnt form of a human leans against the doorway of his chambers, smoke and ash billowing out of his room like cigar smoke, the stench horribly burning the noses of the two elves.<br>
<br>
“Ha… ha… ha… Ow…” the human manages to croak out, slumping against the hall and holding his chest, coughing, holding his tattered robes together with his free hand.<br>
<br>
“NOW what did you do, Trilkin?” an elf muttered, waving the smoke away as he knelt down to examine the wounded human. In the back of his mind, he still questions why he bothers helping the stupid enchanter, but the chanter has done a lot of research… He can’t deny intelligence when he sees it.<br>
<br>
The human could only point in the room at the large storm of smoke.<br>
<br>
“It’s finished. It’s finally finished…” he grinned toothily, looking towards the room.<br>
<br>
“What’s finished, Trilkin? Your newest incendiary device that’s probably going to blow up the temple? You KNOW that you’re going to get your ass flung o—“<br>
<br>
And before he finishes his sentence, he turns to the room, his mouth hanging open in mid sentence as he watches a form shamble out of the room.<br>
<br>
A sarnak…? A… tiny sarnak… A VERY tiny sarnak…?<br>
<br>
“What… in the fuck… is that?”<br>
<br>
“It’s a sarnak! What the hell does it look like?”<br>
<br>
“… It looks like a midget sarnak… Did you cut off half it’s body and attach legs to it or something?”<br>
<br>
“Bah. No. See, I wanted to harness some sort of destructive force to rival the wizard’s ability to burn all their mana into one singular charge. Well, look at him! He may be tiny, but his eventual explosion makes Al`Kabor’s trip to Luclin look like a cheap parlor trick. This baby can blow up all of Antontica in one detonation!”<br>
<br>
“…”<br>
<br>
“…”<br>
<br>
The two elves could only stare down at the sarnak, scratching their arms nervously, their pale skin stretched by their fingers, digging deep red marks into their flesh as they do.<br>
<br>
“You are so gone…”<br>
